									<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top"> 
  <center><b><font size="5" face=verdana color="gold">Mastering Trade Skills</font></b></center>

  <p align="left"> <font face="verdana" size="2">Welcome to the trade skill beginner’s 
    guide. This guide will show you some basics with working with trade skills 
    and tips on how to make the trade skill work better for you. </font>
  <p><font size="2" color="gold" face="verdana"><b>Character Attributes<br>
    </b></font> <font face="verdana" size="2"><br>
    There are three main attributes that will help your trade skill and improve 
    the time and cost it takes to complete the task. </font>
  <p> <font face="verdana" size="2"><b>INT</b> – <i>This will improve how fast 
    you gain skill levels</i><br>
    <b>WIS</b> – <i>This will help your success rate at creating an item</i><br>
    <b>CHA</b> – <i>Increase your Prices with NPC merchants</i><br>
    </font>
  <p><font face="verdana" size="2"><br>
    Unless you are making a mule character (a low level character just to create 
    items with, example would be to create a level one Enchanter and putting points 
    into INT and WIS just for creating banded armor). The best suggestion would 
    be to put most points into what your class requires if its your main character. 
    However you can find different equipment around Norrath that will increase 
    these three main stats and most master traders will create entire suits to 
    wear, depending on what there doing. If the person is learning a new skill 
    (s)he might wear all INT items to increase the skill level quickly, and then 
    switch to Wisdom items to prevent skill failure (losing enchanted platinum 
    ruby Vail hurts the pocket book). </font>
  <p> 
  <table border=0 width='100%' cellspacing=5 cellpadding=5>
    <tr> 
      <td><font color=gold size=2><b><font face="verdana">The Skills</font></b></font></td>
      <td><font size="2" face=verdana color="gold"><b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Tricks 
        of the Trade</b></font></td>
    </tr>
    <tr> 
      <td valign=top><font color=white face=verdana size=2> 
        <p><a href="#1">Alchemy</a> <br>
          <a href="#2">Baking</a> <br>
          <a href="#3">Brewing</a> <br>
          <a href="#4">Blacksmithing</a> <br>
          <a href="#5">Fletching</a> <br>
          <a href="#6">Jewelcraft<br>
          </a><a href="#10">Poison</a><br>
          <a href="#7">Pottery<br>
          </a><a href="#11">Research</a><a href="#8"><br>
          Tailoring</a> <br>
          <a href="#9">Tinkering</a>
        </font></td>
      <td><font size=2 face=verdana> 
        <ul>
          <li>Each trade skill has a different tool for combining the ingredients 
            of that product. In order to make the final product you need to know 
            how to work the tools 
          <li>Never, Never stack your items when you place them into a tools (listed 
            below) always place ONE item in at once. To remove one item from your 
            stack of items in your inventory hold down CTRL and click on the stack 
            you wish to remove an item from. 
          <li>When a project requires a "flask of water" always remember to use 
            store bought kind, never use foraged or summoned water.</li>
        </ul>
        </font></td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p><font face="verdana" size="2"><a name="1"><font color="gold"><b>Alchemy</b></font></a> 
    </font>
  <blockquote> 
    <p><font size="2" face="verdana">Collecting special herbs selected from the 
      finest regions can be found on different vendors located through Norrath. 
      Then combining them inside a Medicine bag to create helpful potions to always 
      carry inside one’s inventory. Alchemy is a skill only received by shamans 
      of the 25<sup>th</sup> circle, and can be a very expensive and hard trade 
      skill to advance in...</font></p>
    <p><font face="verdana" size="2"><a href="default.asp?dest=trade/alchemy">How 
      to Master Alchemy</a><a href="default.asp?dest=trade/arecipes"><br>
      Alchemy Recipes</a><br>
      Alchemy Message Board<br>
      </font></p>
    <p> 
  </blockquote>
  <p><font face="verdana" size="2"><a name="2"><font color="gold"><b>Baking</b></font></a> 
    </font>
  <blockquote><font face="verdana" size="2">Of all the skill within this great 
    land we call Norath, baking is not one of the more lucrative or widely used 
    skills. It may however be one of the more entertaining ones. Just think of 
    the happiness brought on by receiving a rat ear sandwich from a friend for 
    lunch. Or sitting on the bank of Kerra island with a loved one, watching the 
    sunset eating some edible goo. Some things can not be bought with money. </font> 
    <p> <font face="verdana" size="2"><a href="default.asp?dest=trade/baking">How 
      to Master Baking</a><br>
      <a href="default.asp?dest=trade/bakingnpc">NPC Location List</a><br>
      Baking Message Board<br>
      <br>
      </font>
  </blockquote>
  <p><font face="verdana" size="2"><a name="3"><font color="gold"><b>Brewing</b></font></a> 
    </font>
  <blockquote><font face="verdana" size="2">Ah, the taste of a freshly brewed 
    tall glass of beer is quite refreshing don&#146;t you think? A long time ago 
    the skill of brewing use to be almost worthless to some, it would be more 
    of a role-playing skill then a skill that you could consider for profit or 
    any advantage to your character.</font> 
    <p> <font face="verdana" size="2"><a href="default.asp?dest=trade/brewing">How 
      To Master Brewing</a><br>
      <a href="default.asp?dest=trade/brewingnpc">NPC Location List</a><br>
      Brewing Message Board<br>
      <br>
      </font>
  </blockquote>
  <p><font face="verdana" size="2"><a name="4"><font color="gold"><b>Blacksmithing</b></font></a> 
    </font>
  <blockquote><font face="verdana" size="2">The wonders of taking ore and refining 
    into metal have been one of the longest trade skills known to man. Since the 
    dawn of time man created protection for themselves, may that be leather or 
    fine steel plate mail suits the point remained true. Man cannot live in battle 
    very long without protection of the delicate skin that covers his body, for 
    that reason one must create armor to protect against the claw of a dragon 
    or a blade of a Sword.</font> 
    <p> <font face="verdana" size="2"><a href="default.asp?dest=trade/smith">How 
      to Master Smithing </a><br>
